observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:
(a) Inventory Committee
(i) conduct a complete actual physical inventory count of all the PPEs owned by the Municipality pursuant to COA Circular 2020-006;
(ii) exert more effort in securing the needed documents or information in the recognition and valuation of the donated PPEs, otherwise record the same in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006; and

(iii) coordinate with the Accounting Department for the reconciliation of accounting records with the RPCPPE for identification of differences in the PPE;


(b) Municipal Planning and Development Officer, together with the Municipal Assessor, continue locating the 496 properties owned by the Municipality to facilitate the titling thereof;


(c) OIC-Municipal Accountant, together with the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal General Services Officer, initiate the proper recognition and inventory of the Local Road Network System as well as the drafting of the Local Road Network Map of the Municipality; and
(d) Local Chief Executive instruct all department heads account for all donated PPEs under their custody and submit to the Accounting Department all documents pertaining thereto for proper recognition in the books.

We recommended that the 

a. 	Management create an inventory committee to conduct a complete physical count of the PPE owned by the Municipality to determine their actual existence, and for the maintenance of complete property cards, and property, plant and equipment ledger cards;

b. General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant initiate the necessary reconciliation of the accounting records of the PPE accounts balances with the physical inventory report, and reclassify the PPE items in the inventory report to ascertain the actual amount of each PPE account; 

c.	Municipal Accountant determine the remaining useful life of the PPE assets not provided for depreciation to ascertain their carrying value for the correct reporting in the financial statements; and

d. 	General Services Officer determine (i) all the unserviceable PPEs beyond economic repair and have a separate report thereof, and (ii) items for reclassification to inventory accounts for the correct reporting of the PPEs in the inventory report.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require officials to 
(a) 	 refrain from incurring and charging expenses not related to disaster risk reduction and management activities to the DRRM fund pursuant to Republic Act (RA) No. 10121; 

(b) avoid the payment of overtime pay to  Job Orders as prohibited by CSC-DBM Joint Circular No. 1 s. 2015; 


(c) 	 refrain from conducting gatherings wherein social contact may not be avoided; 

(d) submit the lacking documentary requirements as mentioned in Items 1.13, 1.14 and 1.15; and 
(e) ensure compliance with the prescribed guidelines of the GPPB pertaining to the procurement of COVID-related purchases.

